  "prompt": "Do women lactate when they are pregnant?",
  "response": "Yes, women can produce milk during pregnancy, but lactation typically begins in earnest after childbirth. During pregnancy, particularly in the later stages, hormonal changes start the process of breast preparation for milk production. Estrogen and progesterone stimulate the development of milk ducts and the production of colostrum, the first form of milk that is rich in nutrients and antibodies. \n\nWhile some women may notice a small amount of colostrum leaking from their breasts before delivery, most women do not produce significant amounts of milk until after they have given birth, when the hormone prolactin rises significantly following the delivery of the placenta. This increase in prolactin is crucial for establishing and maintaining milk supply for breastfeeding.",
